{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538347","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538347"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:27:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:27:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16166"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16166","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16166"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.47,0.21,0.07,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8857"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64184"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8857","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8857"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16166"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49616"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1238"},{"type":"tags","id":"1969"},{"type":"tags","id":"2128"},{"type":"tags","id":"2793"},{"type":"tags","id":"4647"},{"type":"tags","id":"4820"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"},{"type":"tags","id":"12962"},{"type":"tags","id":"12969"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21103"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35913"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43617"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44433"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64184","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64184"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic requesting advice about a positive ureaplasma PCR result on urine testing. She denies any symptoms, but recently ordered a home testing kit from an online provider as part of routine sexual health screening. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications except for the combined oral contraceptive pill. She has had two sexual partners in the past year and uses condoms inconsistently. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. External genitalia appear normal with no discharge or lesions. Urine pregnancy test is negative.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral doxycycline","Reassurance that no treatment is required","Repeat PCR testing in three months","Referral for treatment by a sexual health physician","Oral azithromycin"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case highlights an increasingly common clinical scenario where private testing leads to detection of normal commensal organisms. \u003Cem\u003EUreaplasma urealyticum\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EUreaplasma parvum\u003C/em\u003E are part of the normal urogenital microbiome, with colonisation rates of 40-80% in sexually active women. Testing for ureaplasma is specifically excluded from evidence-based STI screening guidelines.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance that no treatment is required\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management. The consultation provides an opportunity for education about appropriate STI screening, which includes testing for chlamydia, gonorrhoea, HIV, and syphilis in sexually active young adults. The presence of ureaplasma in an asymptomatic person represents colonisation rather than infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral doxycycline\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate and potentially harmful. Unnecessary antibiotic use can lead to resistance, alteration of the normal microbiome, and side effects. Treatment of ureaplasma is only considered in specific clinical scenarios such as recurrent non-gonococcal urethritis where other causes have been excluded, or in some cases of infertility investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat PCR testing\u003C/strong\u003E would perpetuate unnecessary health anxiety and costs. Follow-up testing is not indicated as the initial test should not have been performed. This highlights the importance of pre-test counselling and following evidence-based screening guidelines.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral for treatment by a sexual health physician\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary for asymptomatic detection of a commensal organism. However, given the patient\u0027s inconsistent condom use, appropriate counselling about safe sexual practices and routine STI screening should be provided in primary care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral azithromycin\u003C/strong\u003E, like doxycycline, represents unnecessary antimicrobial therapy. While some studies have investigated associations between ureaplasma and conditions such as bacterial vaginosis or adverse pregnancy outcomes, there is insufficient evidence to support routine treatment even in these contexts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe increasing availability of direct-to-consumer testing has created new challenges in clinical practice. Healthcare providers must be prepared to counsel patients about the interpretation of such results and the distinction between colonisation and infection. This case emphasises the importance of evidence-based screening guidelines and antimicrobial stewardship.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ureaplasma species are considered normal urethral flora and testing is not indicated in routine STI screening.","Asymptomatic patients with incidental detection of ureaplasma do not require treatment.","Private, unreferred testing can lead to unnecessary anxiety about colonisation with commensal organisms."],"references":["Tz Kotrotsiou, M Exindari, Diza E, G Gioula, A Melidou, Kaplanis K, et al. Prevalence and antimicrobial susceptibility of Ureaplasma urealyticum in asymptomatic women in Northern Greece. Hippokratia. 2020;17(4):319. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4097411","Rak K, Aneta Kiecka, Bia\u0142ecka J, Kawalec A, Pawe\u0142 Krzy\u015bciak, Bia\u0142ecka A. Retrospective Analysis of the Ureaplasma spp. Prevalence with Reference to Other Genital Tract Infections in Women of Reproductive Age. Polish Journal of Microbiology. 2022 Nov 20;71(4):509\u201318. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9944971/","Raynes-Greenow CH, Roberts CL, Bell JC, Peat B, Gilbert GL, Parker S. Antibiotics for ureaplasma in the vagina in pregnancy. Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews. 2011 Sep 7. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7133540/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49616"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16166"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49616","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49616"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-23T04:15:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-27T16:25:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8857"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64184"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"he